<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note8" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">8</A>
Perdiccas did in fact act as sole regent, but by the terms of the settlement the power was divided between him and Craterus, and Meleager was made Perdiccas' lieutenant (Dexippus, <I>FGrH</I>, 100.8.4; Arrian, <I>FGrH</I>, 156.1.1‑3;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte13.html#4
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 13.4.5</A>). Diodorus omits any reference to the expected son of Roxanê, who was to share the throne with Arrhidaeus, but beginning with chapter 18.6<!-- DON'T LINK --> he regularly speaks of the kings rather than of the king.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note9" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref9
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">9</A>
This list of satrapies and satraps agrees, with the exceptions noted below, with that in Dexippus (<I>FGrH</I>, 100.8). Arrian (<I>FGrH</I>, 156.1.5‑8) and Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#10
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(10.10.1‑6)
	</A>
also agree, but do not include the eastern satrapies. Justin
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte13.html#4
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(13.4.9‑25)
	</A>
is very inaccurate.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note10" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">10</A>
Media Maior: cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#note16
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">on § 3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note11" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref11
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">11</A>
Arrian assigns this command jointly to Antipater and Craterus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note12" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref12
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">12</A>
Cp. Book 17.<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17E*.html#86.7
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">86.7</A>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17E*.html#89.6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
89.6</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note13" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref13
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">13</A>
<I>i.e.</I> the Hindu Kush.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note14" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref14
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">14</A>
Dexippus gives this name as Rhadaphernes.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note15" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref15
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">15</A>
Dexippus gives this name as Neoptolemus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note16" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref16
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">16</A>
Atropates, <SPAN CLASS="whole">father-in‑law</SPAN> of Perdiccas, had been satrap of all Media (Arrian, <I>Anabasis</I>, 4.18.3, 7.4.5<!--</A>ARRIAN:ANABASIS-->). He now retained the north-west portion, henceforth known as Lesser


<A ID="p19x"></A>Media or Media Atropatenê, which soon became independent and was ruled by his descendants for many years
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/11M*.html#13
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Strabo, 11.13.1)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note17" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">17</A>
In spite of Justin
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte13.html#4
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(13.4.6)</A>, this is not Philip Arrhidaeus, the king. Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18B*.html#26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 26‑28
	</A>
and
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18B*.html#36.7
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
36.7</A>. Pausanias
	<A HREF="
https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0160:book=1:chapter=6
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pausanias,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(1.6.3)
	</A>
states that the body was to be buried in Macedon, and Arrian (<I>FGrH</I>, 156.9.25) implies that the body was not to go to Egypt.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
A pity for us that Alexander was not buried in Macedon! Some of the Macedonian royal tombs were discovered intact in 1977 with the bodies of his son and maybe his half-brother as well: see
	<A HREF="
https://www.livius.org/articles/place/aegae-vergina/
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
the Aegae page at Livius</A>.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note18" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref18
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">18</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#109
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Book 17.109.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note19" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref19
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">19</A>
For a discussion of these plans in general, and in particular of the plan for invading Africa and Europe, see W. W. Tarn, <I>Journal of Hellenic Studies</I>, 49 (1939), pp124‑135<!--</A>ARRIAN:ANABASIS-->; and C. A. Robinson, Jr., <I>American Journal of Philology</I>, 61 (1940), pp402‑412<!--</A>JOURNAL-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note20" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref20
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">20</A>
Since the pyre had already been completed
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#114
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Book 17.114‑115)</A>, the reference here appears to be to the tomb planned by Alexander
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#72.3
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 72.3)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A>
The attack is to be directed against the non-Greeks on the northern coast of Africa and on the southern coast of Europe from Spain to Sicily. Cp. Arrian, <I>Anabasis</I>, 7.1.1‑4<!--</A>ARRIAN:ANABASIS-->;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#1.17
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 10.1.17‑18</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/10.html#68
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 68.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note22" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A>
Cyrnus in Macedon is otherwise unknown, but the name is found elsewhere in Greece (<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/9B*.html#105
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Herodotus, 9.105</A>;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/4*.html#53
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pliny, <I>Natural History</I>, 4.53</A>), and the change to Cyrrhus, although easy, seems unnecessary.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/13A1*.html#1.26
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo, 13.1.26</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/1C*.html#63.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Book 1.63.2‑9</A>. Antipater of Sidon (<I>Pal. Anthol.</I> 9.58), an epigrammatist of the second century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, gives the following as the seven wonders of the world: The walls of Babylon, the statue of Zeus by Pheidias, the hanging gardens of Babylon, the Colossus of Rhodes, the pyramids of Egypt, the Mausoleum at Halicarnassus, and the Temple of Artemis at Ephesus. Other lists combine the walls and the hanging gardens of Babylon, and add the Pharos at Alexandria.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref25
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A>
Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/10*.html#9.18
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(10.9.18)
	</A>
says three hundred. Cp. Arrian, <I>FGrH</I>, 156.1.4.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#2.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 2.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note27" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref27
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27</A>
<I>i.e.</I> those of the far eastern part of the empire.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A>
The Caucasus is the Hindu Kush. The Eastern Ocean is specifically the Bay of Bengal, but thought of as forming the eastern boundary of Asia. The division of Asia by the Taurus Range follows Eratosthenes (Strabo,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/2A1*.html#1
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
2.1.1</A>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/2E2*.html#5.31
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
2.5.31‑32</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A>
These three bodies of water are, respectively, the Arabian Sea, the Bay of Bengal (called the Eastern Ocean above), and the Persian Gulf. "This continent" is probably Asia.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A>
Properly the Don, but here the Oxus (modern Amu-Darya), or possibly the Jaxartes (Syr-Darya), both of which are frequently confused with the Don by ancient writers; or, perhaps, are thought to be part of the Don River system.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
This name is sometimes applied to the whole of the Caspian Sea, sometimes to its eastern portion only. Eratosthenes


<A ID="p27x"></A>and later Greek geographers in general believed that the Caspian was a gulf of the Northern Ocean (Strabo,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/2A1*.html#17
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
2.1.17</A>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/2E2*.html#5.18
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
2.5.18</A>), but Herodotus
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/1D*.html#203
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(1.203.1)
	</A>
had already called it an inland sea.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
In
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/2B*.html#37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Book 2.35‑37</A>, Diodorus discusses India, which he states to be square, bounded on south and east by the "Great Sea" (the Indian Ocean or the Bay of Bengal), on the west by the Indus, and on the north by the mountains. Of the southern extension of India he knows nothing.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A>
They are said to have had four thousand war elephants (Books <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/2B*.html#37.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2.37.3</A>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17E*.html#93.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
17.93.2</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A>
In
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/2B*.html#37.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Book 2.37.2
	</A>
the width is given as thirty stades, but in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17E*.html#93.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Book 17.93.2
	</A>
it is <SPAN CLASS="whole">thirty-two</SPAN>. Strabo
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/15A2*.html#1.35
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(15.1.35)
	</A>
quotes Megasthenes as giving it a width of one hundred stades <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('about 19 km',WIDTH,132)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>(about twelve miles).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
By some geographers the Nile was regarded as the boundary between Asia and Libya-Africa
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/1D*.html#4.7
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Strabo, 1.4.7)</A>; others included Egypt in Asia
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/2E2*.html#5.33
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Strabo 2.5.33)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
For earlier unrest in these satrapies see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17E*.html#99.5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Book 17.99.5‑6</A>;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/9*.html#7
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 9.7.1‑11</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/18A*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
For the Lamian War see Arrian, <I>FGrH</I>, 156.1.9, 12; Plutarch,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Demosthenes*.html#27
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
